  "texts": [
    "Removal orders from authorities must be complied with immediately, subject to judicial redress possibilities.Hosting services must also share information with national authorities regarding actions taken against illegal content (Article 31).Additional safeguards are mandated against the submission of incorrect or unsubstantiated notices, to avoid the removal of legal content (Recital 49).",
    "Penalties for misuse can include court injunctions and financial compensation for reputational damage.",
    "Hosting services must also facilitate counter-notices by affected users disputing removal decisions, to enable users to dispute wrongful takedowns (Recital 50), and reinstate content where counter-notices are valid.",
    "Extensive transparency reporting requirements cover notice volumes, action taken, counter-notice amounts, and restored content percentages.Advertising transparency requirements (Articles 24, 26, 39) To enable meaningful public insight into the opaque processes around targeted online advertising, Articles 24 and 30 of the DSA impose detailed transparency duties on online platforms regarding ads shown to users, specifically those related to political messaging or important public debates.Article 30 mandates collection of trader identity and location data by platforms facilitating consumer-to-business transactions, improving traceability and accountability.",
    "In addition, Article 26 requires clear markings identifying paid ads directly in ad interfaces, as well as disclosures on VLOPs face additional duties like collecting and publishing advertiser identity and verification information."
  ],
